│ stop({"edit_points": [[249, 251, "llvm/lib/Transforms/IPO/SCCP.cpp"]],      │
│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue: The crash occurs in                │
│ `DomTreeUpdater::validateDeleteBB` with an assertion failure that a basic   │
│ block being deleted still has predecessors. This indicates that the pass is │
│ attempting to delete a basic block that is still referenced by other        │
│ blocks' terminators.\n\n2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log: The debug log shows that  │
│ during SCCP processing, dead blocks are identified and marked for deletion. │
│ Specifically, the log shows:\n```\n  BasicBlock Dead:\nloop:                │
│ ; preds = %loop, %entry\n  %add = or i32 0, 0\n  %cond = icmp eq i32 %arg,  │
│ 1\n  br i1 %cond, label %exit, label %loop\n  BasicBlock Dead:\nexit:       │
│ ; preds = %loop\n  ret i32 0\n```\nHowever, looking at the debugger output, │
│ we can see that the `loop` block still has a predecessor (`entry` block)    │
│ that branches to it, and the `loop` block itself has been transformed to    │
│ contain only `unreachable`.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis: The issue is in the  │
│ `runIPSCCP` function in `SCCP.cpp`. The code collects dead blocks in        │
│ `BlocksToErase` (line 222) and later calls `changeToUnreachable` on them    │
│ (lines 237-243). However, `changeToUnreachable` only replaces the           │
│ instructions in the block with `unreachable` but doesn't remove the block   │
│ from its predecessors' successor lists. Then, when the code tries to delete │
│ these blocks via `DTU.deleteBB(DeadBB)` (line 251), the dominator tree      │
│ updater correctly detects that the block still has predecessors and         │
│ asserts.\n\nThe problem is that `changeToUnreachable` should have already   │
│ handled updating the CFG by removing the block from its predecessors, but   │
│ this only happens when `changeToUnreachable` is called on the first         │
│ instruction of a block that is being made unreachable. However, in this     │
│ case, the blocks are already marked as dead and contain only unreachable    │
│ instructions, so calling `changeToUnreachable` again doesn't properly       │
│ update the CFG.\n\nLooking more carefully at the flow: the blocks are added │
│ to `BlocksToErase` because they are not executable (line 215-223). Then     │
│ `changeToUnreachable` is called on them (lines 237-243), which should       │
│ update the CFG by removing the block from its successors' predecessor       │
│ lists, but it doesn't remove the block from its predecessors' successor     │
│ lists. The predecessors still have branches pointing to these dead          │
│ blocks.\n\nThe correct approach is to ensure that before deleting a block,  │
│ all of its predecessors have their terminator instructions updated to not   │
│ branch to the dead block. However, the current code structure has a flaw:   │
│ it calls `changeToUnreachable` which handles successor updates but not      │
│ predecessor updates for the block being deleted.\n\nActually, looking more  │
│ closely at `changeToUnreachable` implementation, it does call               │
│ `Successor->removePredecessor(BB, PreserveLCSSA)` for each successor, which │
│ removes the block from its successors' predecessor lists. But it doesn't    │
│ handle the reverse - it doesn't update the predecessors to stop pointing to │
│ this block.\n\nThe real issue is that when we have a block that is dead but │
│ still has predecessors pointing to it, we cannot simply delete it. We need  │
│ to first update all predecessors to not branch to it. The                   │
│ `changeToUnreachable` function is designed to make a block unreachable by   │
│ replacing its contents, but it assumes the block is still part of the CFG.  │
│ For complete block removal, we need to handle the predecessor               │
│ updates.\n\nHowever, looking at the specific case in the reproducer, the    │
│ `loop` block has a self-loop and an entry predecessor. When SCCP determines │
│ the block is dead, it should have already updated the control flow to not   │
│ reach this block. The fact that the entry block still has a branch to       │
│ `loop` suggests that the edge removal wasn't properly handled.\n\nThe root  │
│ cause is that the code is trying to delete blocks that still have           │
│ predecessors. The fix is to ensure that blocks are only deleted if they     │
│ truly have no predecessors, or to properly handle the predecessor cleanup   │
│ before deletion.\n\nLooking at the LLVM infrastructure, the proper way to   │
│ delete a basic block is to ensure all its predecessors have been updated to │
│ not branch to it. The `changeToUnreachable` function doesn't do this - it   │
│ only handles the successor side.\n\nThe correct fix is to not attempt to    │
│ delete blocks that still have predecessors. Instead, we should only delete  │
│ blocks that are truly isolated (no predecessors and no successors).         │
│ Alternatively, we should use a different mechanism to remove dead blocks    │
│ that properly handles the CFG updates.\n\nBut actually, examining the code  │
│ more carefully, the issue is that `BlocksToErase` contains blocks that may  │
│ still be referenced by other blocks. The `changeToUnreachable` calls (lines │
